    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2559133961" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2559133961" />
    <a title="Benoît" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8593248-beno-t"><img alt="Benoît" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1538568913p2/8593248.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2559133961?book_show_action=true">Oct 11, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Benoît" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Benoît" href="/user/show/8593248-beno-t">Benoît</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2559133961" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8449011300193315943">La Mort est mon Métier (Death is my Trade, 1952) is a fictionalized portrait of Rudolph Höss, who commanded the concentration camp of Auschwitz during its crucial years of extermination. It tells his life from what was known and from what he said of it in the memoirs he was instructed to write during his trial. As a commander, he personally designed the installations in Auschwitz, under direct order from Himmler (by far the most fascinatingly scary character in the book), and can be considered t</span>
  <span id="freeText8449011300193315943" style="display:none">La Mort est mon Métier (Death is my Trade, 1952) is a fictionalized portrait of Rudolph Höss, who commanded the concentration camp of Auschwitz during its crucial years of extermination. It tells his life from what was known and from what he said of it in the memoirs he was instructed to write during his trial. As a commander, he personally designed the installations in Auschwitz, under direct order from Himmler (by far the most fascinatingly scary character in the book), and can be considered to have assassinated 2.5 millions people, which is his estimate.<br /><br />The interest of the book of course lies between the psychological and moral question: what kind of conscience can you have when you organize mass killings, when you organize death ? I personally do not believe that following orders (the common defense) was all everyone thought there was to it. Still, you must probably come to believe it's a necessity over which you personally have no control and no responsibility, and you just focus on your own very modest life as soldier (in a bubble). Those questions are forever unresolved.<br /><br />The scenes in the camp are the most difficult but also the best, as frankly, I do not overly care about the character's background and relation to this unloving authoritative father. Merle is faithful at least, which is good, and he makes clear enough that Rudolph has no sensitivity for human life in the context of war (otherwise, he's just polite, reserved, weird in his matter-of-factedness). The scenes in Auschwitz are successful because Merle shows the terribleness and surreal absurdity of Rudolph Höss' zealous struggle to simply make his camp function and to bring Himmler's plans to reality. Which he does. And that is why he was chosen, as he said many times: he's good at organization. What is terrifying is that he apparently wasn't cynical, it's what he believed. For whatever it's worth, after showing absolute detachment during his trial, and while he could have no doubt over his eventual sentence, Höss apparently began to feel doubt about what he had done, about the rightfulness of the orders, and expressed a very late regret. Hard to believe, yes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8449011300193315943" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

