    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2487014496" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2487014496" />
    <a title="Dalma Vatai" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/82471557-dalma-vatai"><img alt="Dalma Vatai" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2487014496?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dalma Vatai" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dalma Vatai" href="/user/show/82471557-dalma-vatai">Dalma Vatai</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/12210966-mesters-gem-a-hal-l">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2487014496&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2487014496" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14218321578494286456">Merle, in his fictional biography of Rudolf Hoess, the Commandant of Auschwitz, imagines Hoess as someone whose life was, from the very beginning, shaped by obedience. Obedience was the highest virtue in his world, and something without which he did not feel any sense of accomplishment or self-worth. Fictional Hoess (and very likely real-life Hoess as well) did not have his own thoughts, beliefs, feelings, emotions, etc., thus, his entire being was an embodiment of the commands he was given. Thi</span>
  <span id="freeText14218321578494286456" style="display:none">Merle, in his fictional biography of Rudolf Hoess, the Commandant of Auschwitz, imagines Hoess as someone whose life was, from the very beginning, shaped by obedience. Obedience was the highest virtue in his world, and something without which he did not feel any sense of accomplishment or self-worth. Fictional Hoess (and very likely real-life Hoess as well) did not have his own thoughts, beliefs, feelings, emotions, etc., thus, his entire being was an embodiment of the commands he was given. This conditioning comes from his father, who, I would argue, had the worst impact on Hoess of all people. His entire existence was determined by the kinds of commands he was given; this, coupled with the fervent nationalism and anti-Semitism of interwar Germany, proved lethal for millions of Jews and others. But nationalism and anti-Semitism in themselves would not have been enough to make Auschwitz the disaster that it was made to be; I believe the most crucial component was Hoess' pathological obsession with obeying commands and his being able to derive a sense of accomplishment from obeying commands only. I think it is also important to note that he never received love as a child: his parents did not provide him with love, care, or connection, so he was never able to build those things later in life. This helped him detach from the deaths of millions that happened before his very eyes; he was simply unable to connect to other people, and so unable to feel anything like love or sympathy towards them. <br />I believe this book is a crucial piece of the vast literature on the Holocaust, as it illuminates the psychological background of Hoess' seemingly incomprehensible inhumanity, and possibly that of many others.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14218321578494286456" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

