        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2434162471" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14593091023595738005">The book “Death Is My Trade” was an attempt to submerge into the mind of the man responsible for leading one of the death camps Auschwitz. His profile as a soldier just listening to the orders is I think quite accurate, but his lack of simple human emotions is really disturbing. The main character does not recognize humans sent to death as human beings, but as units he was assigned to take care of. His problem is not with the killing, but with getting rid of the bodies. He has no philosophical p</span>
  <span id="freeText14593091023595738005" style="display:none">The book “Death Is My Trade” was an attempt to submerge into the mind of the man responsible for leading one of the death camps Auschwitz. His profile as a soldier just listening to the orders is I think quite accurate, but his lack of simple human emotions is really disturbing. The main character does not recognize humans sent to death as human beings, but as units he was assigned to take care of. His problem is not with the killing, but with getting rid of the bodies. He has no philosophical problems with the killing of more than a million people, his difficulties with this task are purely technical.<br />The main character is even with his lack of human trades quite believable. Author provides the story of his whole life, his problems with crazy father, his obsession with order and war, the presence and sympathy to NSDAP and also why he was chosen to lead the camp by Heinrich Himmler.<br />I can’t judge whether it’s an accurate mental description of the real Rudolf Höß, but it makes you think about this man a lot.</span>
